## Executive Summary
In this lab, I analyze the cybersecurity dangers of implementing
IoT devices in cities and transportation, as smart cities require
thousands to millions of connected devices to operate, creating an
attack surface for cybercriminals. The most recent example
of a cyberattack on a smart city was back in June 2023, in the city
of Olsztyn, Poland, a cyberattack paralyzed its transportation
infrastructure, by hitting at least a hundred intersections in the 
city centre, causing accidents, traffic jams, and public disruption. 
While implementing technology in cities can provide quality of life 
improvements to the residents, it can also cause major disruption as 
emergency, security alert systems, street video surveillance, and smart
traffic lights are among the most vulnerable to cyberattacks.

---

## Technical Analysis
### The Vulnerability
Smart traffic systems use video detection, IoT sensors, AI, and cloud 
computing to monitor and improve traffic flow. While having adaptive traffic
management systems that can adjust the flow of traffic can improve safety,
they can also offer an attack surface for cyberattacks.

Due to the extended attack surface a smart city provides to an attacker from the
thousands of connected devices, one unpatched device can open the door to an attacker
for the entire system. Many traffic light systems follow weak security practices, such as
default manufacturer credentials that are never changed, lack of encryption for firmware 
or communication channels, and lack of authentication mechanisms for the data they receive from 
their sensors, giving a threat actor, the opportunity to push a malware firmware update 
to gain control over the device.

### How the Attack Works
The attacker managed to access the system either by exploiting weak credentials or by 
leveraging unpatched software versions. By gaining access to one unpatched device, they 
likely entered the entire transit system.

The attack took place at the city of Olsztyn, Poland, in June of 2023, when it suffered 
from a cyberattack that disrupted the city's transit system. It targeted 92 intersections
disrupting traffic lights and the metropolitan ticket sales system, forcing transit authorities
to shut down the servers for several weeks, making the intersections and the metropolitan 
ticket system non-operational during that period.

### What the Attacker Gained
The attack successfully forced transit authorities to shut down the system, while
the authorities worked to identify and contain the vulnerability. With the metropolitan ticket system 
offline, the city faced significant financial losses, while demonstrating how an attacker can hold
an entire city center hostage, and without access to critical infrastructure for several weeks.

Beyond the immediate damage, the attack demonstrated that a single entry point in a poorly 
secured IoT network can render an entire city centre without access to critical infrastructure 
for weeks. Smart city systems can be targeted by ransomware groups and hacktivists that seek
to cause public disruption with the least amount of technical investment.

---

## Impact Assessment
Cyberattacks in smart cities can endanger public safety, as disrupted traffic lights
are not just an inconvenience, but intersection failures and emergency vehicles delays
can have life-threatening consequences.

This attack on Olsztyn, Poland, is likely only one of the many smart cities that
use the same vulnerable equipment. As smart cities grow in numbers, so will the 
destructive cyberattacks against them. A simple security mistake, like using 
default or weak credentials and delayed software patching, can disrupt
an entire city for weeks, even costing human lives.

---

## Mitigation & Recommendations
Individually, the city authorities should force the mandatory replacement of 
default credentials with strong credential policies on all deployed devices
on the network, alongside regularly scheduled patch management, and introducing network 
segmentation to limit lateral movement in the event of a breach.

As an industry providing IoT services, and especially in the public sectors
where government departments are in charge of them and not security 
professionals, implementing strong security fundamentals, like 
encryption, firmware updates and no default credentials can limit the 
attack surface for an attacker.

Maintaining and securing infrastructure only after a cyberattack has 
occurred is a reactive stance that will never be sufficient. Security 
must be enforced at the manufacturing stage, before systems reach deployment.
The EU Cyber Resilience Act, passed in 2024, now requires manufacturers to 
follow security standards before ever selling into the EU market.

